post_text:
NPE staff and teachers and others from the community cheered on the participants of the Crozer EMS 9/11 Memorial Bike Ride today as they cycled from Crozer EMS HQ to Rose Tree Media Park. The annual ride is to honor those lost on this day nineteen years ago as well as first responders from Delaware County.

We remember and honor all of those who lost their lives on 9/11/01 on this National Day of Service and Remembrance and Patriot Day. #NeverForget

post_text:
The second week of school is underway, and August 31st feels so long ago already. Usually we go around to all of our schools on the first day to capture the wonderful moments of our community reconnecting and the excitement of the new school year. Then we share photos and a video highlighting the day.

We did the same this year, thanks to your help! Thank you for sharing photos and videos on this page and at pr@wssd.org. (Sorry if we missed any!)

The start of this year looks a lot different than previous years, but we are still WSSD, back TOGETHER and in this TOGETHER! Here is a glimpse of what day one of the 2020-2021 school year looked like. So happy to see your faces, smiles, and smiling eyes!

Please keep sharing any photos or clips with us as we may use it in social media or on our website. Thanks! Have a great school year!

We are excited to have our teachers and staff back as a week of in-service began today before school starts on August 31st. There were meetings, a virtual convocation, supplies and material organizing, reconnecting with colleagues, and final preparations for virtual learning ~ the start of a very busy week. They are looking forward to meeting with their students very soon! We are grateful for their dedication, creativity, and flexibility, and we know they will continue to rise to the challenges and opportunities that this school year presents.‚ù§Ô∏è

Energetic photo courtesy of the first grade team at WES!

Strath Haven Class of 2020 graduates were all smiles as they stopped by the high school on August 8th to pick up prizes, usually given out at the After Prom. They selected a numbered card and then got the corresponding prize which included gift cards, Spikeball sets, AirPods, Yeti water bottles, Bluetooth speakers, laptops, TVs, and more. It wasn't the same as the usual end of year activities, but we are thankful to the generosity of our SHHS parents who worked so hard to give the graduates a special send-off. Thanks to the After Prom Committee for organizing! Best of luck to the Haven Class of 2020 - you will be missed!

post_text:
Alicia Gabe, SHHS '11 has been creating chalk art to spread joy during these uncertain times. Check out some of her cartoon characters (and Dwight) that she has drawn on the sidewalk outside Nether Providence Elementary School for local families to enjoy. The rain may have washed them away, but she will be back to draw some more. She was very happy to see that some children were also drawing their own designs there after she started!

Alicia is currently studying organizational development and leadership at Widener University and works full-time in the human resources department at PNC Bank. She loves art and enjoyed her art classes at WSSD, particularly one at Strath Haven HS with Mrs. Rodgers.

Thanks, Alicia! Beautiful work!

Congratulations to Gretha Fergus '22 who was selected by the National Association for Music Education to the All-National Honor Ensembles choir! She is invited to perform in Orlando in November. At Strath Haven High School, Gretha is a member of Camerata, Cantata and The Strath Haven Silvertones and performs in the school musicals.

Gretha moved to Pennsylvania in the seventh grade and began studying with voice teacher Val Haber. She primarily sings classical music and sings pieces in German, Italian, and French. This summer she participated in a virtual singing camp with the Houston Grand Opera and volunteers at Opera Philadelphia. She hopes to study singing in college.

Mr. Shankweiler shares: "Gretha is a diligent, hard-working musician. She is an artful singer and, above all, she is a wonderfully kind individual."

Congrats, Gretha! #wssdmusic #havenproud

Today is the 155th anniversary of Juneteenth, the oldest nationally-celebrated commemoration of the ending of slavery in the United States. If you are unfamiliar with the day, the National Museum of African American History and Culture provides a brief explanation of its history and significance: https://nmaahc.si.edu/blog-post/historical-legacy-juneteenth

Also check out the National Geographic article: "Why Juneteenth is a Celebration of Hope". https://www.nationalgeographic.com/history/2020/06/juneteenth-celebration-hope/#close

Teaching Tolerance offers a great resource for parents and families to learn more about this day: https://www.tolerance.org/magazine/teaching-juneteenth

Today we will take time to learn, listen, and reflect.

Congratulations to all of the Strath Haven High School students who received Varsity Arts Awards this year! Although we were not able to have our usual assembly, we still wanted to make sure that they were recognized for how their talents, passions, and accomplishments enhance Strath Haven and our community.

The Varsity Arts Association was founded in the 1984-1985 school year to reward student contributions in the fields of visual arts, writing, publishing, music, oratory, performing arts, and dance. Faculty advisors for each extracurricular activity elect the students who will receive the awards.

The criteria for membership in the association are:

- Demonstrated development and growth of the student‚Äôs talent.
- Demonstrated use of the student‚Äôs talent in service to the school
- Outstanding achievement in the arts for a body of work.

#havenproud

It is Graduation Eve for the Strath Haven High School Class of 2020. Tomorrow they will receive their diplomas and get ready to take the next step in their journey.

Tonight they would like to thank their teachers, coaches, staff members, administrators, and everyone else who helped them get to this point!

Please join the community to cheer them on during the Class of 2020 Car Parade. And then light up your front porches and houses at 8:20 p.m. (20:20) to give them a rousing send-off. More details and map route are here: wssd.org/seniorcelebration.

Congratulations, graduates!

post_text:
Strath Haven High School Graduation
Student Speaker: Gabrielle McGinn
St. John Chrysostom, SHHS
College: Ursinus College

Gabrielle is one of two student speakers who was selected to share a speech at graduation. Tune in to watch the SHHS Class of 2020 graduation ceremony on Friday, June 5th at 5 p.m. on the District YouTube channel:

youtube.com/c/WallingfordSwarthmoreSchoolDistrict

"I felt compelled to apply because during these times of uncertainty it's hard to remain optimistic. However I wanted to remind people of the power of hope and that even though life isn't how anyone expected it right now, there is always something to be hopeful about. I wanted to write a piece that applied to everyone's life and served as a reminder to take time and evaluate yourself as a person."

Favorite Strath Haven Memory: Playing varsity volleyball all four years.

Favorite teacher: Ms. Ron because of her loving and free-spirited personality.

#strathhaven2020

post_text:
Whether in the classroom, on the playing field, or in the weight room, Mr. Erik Hollingsworth, SHHS special education teacher, football coach, colleague, and friend is always there for others with passion, enthusiasm, and encouragement. He was selected by the Class of 2020 to be their faculty speaker at graduation.

Mr. Hollingsworth has been teaching and working with adolescents since 1997 and teaching at Strath Haven since 2011. He is honored to be this year's speaker for the Class of 2020. He writes:

"This is a class that exemplifies the true meaning of Grit!! This is a special class. Their setbacks will propel their determination. They will always hold a place in the hearts of our community. I am proud to call them brothers and sisters of the Haven Alumni! GID!!"

We are looking forward to hearing his and others' speeches on Friday, June 5th when the Strath Haven HS Class of 2020 Graduation Ceremony which will be premiered on the District YouTube channel at 5 p.m. Be sure to tune in!

youtube.com/c/WallingfordSwarthmoreSchoolDistrict

#SHHS2020

post_text:
The Strath Haven HS literary magazine, Jabberwocky, just published their first online edition. Ms. Drew, faculty advisor, and the leadership team are very excited to showcase the voices, perspectives, and talents of our student artists and writers and to share them with the community.

The magazine's core leadership includes Fran Kenney, Lilian Liu, Evelyn Blanchette, Nina Li, and Lauren St. Clair. This year's featured writers are Eric Tao and Ainsley Wilson.

They have dedicated this year's magazine to Andrea LaPira and all of the Haven teachers who have worked tirelessly and creatively in the shift to remote instruction.

Well done to all. Be sure to check it out!

post_text:
Graduation for our Strath Haven HS seniors is getting closer! Tomorrow is the last day of classes for them, and then it is a week to go until graduation on June 5th.

Seniors, we have missed seeing you in the school hallways, in your classrooms, on the playing fields, on stage, and everywhere you and the rest of our students should be.

One of the bright spots is that it has been nice to see the decorated doors of the Class of 2020 throughout the community and see a little bit of who you are and what is next for you. Here is a close-up of some of those doors and a message to our senior students and families: you mean so much to us! Thank you for being YOU! You will be missed.

Here is a close-up of some of those doors and a message to our senior students and families: you mean so much to us! Thank you for being YOU! You will be missed.

post_text:
WES fifth grade student Ryan played Taps on Memorial Day after a friend sent him a link to the "Taps Across America" story featured on CBS.

Since most Memorial Day events were canceled, On the Road with Steve Hartman teamed up with retired Air Force bugler Jari Villanueva "to keep the spirit of the holiday alive" with this musical initiative.

Veterans, musicians, teachers, and students played Taps on their front lawns, porches, and driveways at 3 p.m., joining together for a moment to honor fallen service members and victims of the coronavirus pandemic.

Ryan has many family members who have served in the armed forces including his aunt, grandfather, two great grandfathers, a great-great grandfather, cousins, and uncles. He misses school, his friends, and his music teacher, Mr. Greenhalgh, and wanted to do something to commemorate the day and honor those who lost their lives serving our country. Thank you, Ryan!

https://www.cbsnews.com/news/how-to-participate-in-steve-hartmans-taps-across-america/ #tapsacrossamerica CBS Philly #wssdmusic #CBStaps

SHMS 7th grade student and tuba player, Greg Guron recently had a very cool, life-changing experience!

Greg and his mother are fans of The Philadelphia Orchestra, and regularly attended concerts at the The Kimmel Center for the Performing Arts.

Early in May, they noticed on the orchestra's web page that tubist Carol Jantsch was offering a contest to low brass players of all ages in the area. Participants had to submit a recording of themselves playing a solo, and the winner would receive a free virtual private music lesson with her.

With a lot of hard work, an abundance of support from his family, and some zoom coaching, Greg won honorable mention! He had his virtual lesson with Ms. Jantsch on May 20th. It was a very positive experience during challenging times. Great job, Greg!

#wssdmusic #havenproud Philadelphia Orchestra Musicians

WES fifth grade student Dominique Bottino and her parents were featured on 6abc Action News about the Eagles Autism Foundation's annual event, the Eagles Autism Challenge which was supposed to have been on Saturday. Thousands would have come together to bike, run, or walk at Lincoln Financial Field. They are disappointed to miss it but are keeping busy with activities such as Sensory Saturday and looking forward to next year's event. We are proud of you, Dominique!

Thanks to Matteo Iadonisi at 6ABC for reporting.

Strath Haven High School student photographers are sharing their work on their new Smugmug site, Haven Photo. Check out so many great memories from the 2019-2020 school year!

shhsphoto.smugmug.com

The students worked with Ms. Plows to create a place to highlight their work and share with the community. Special shout-out to Ben Ainslie who did the lion's share of the work on the site, including teaching others how to use it! They are excited to share their work with you and ask that you make every effort to credit the student photographer if you download and share photos. Photographers‚Äô names will pop up with each image. To download for free, please make sure to read through the instructions and use the download arrow on the left-side toolbar. Recently, language arts students at SHMS had the chance to explore "Blackout Poetry." Blackout Poetry is a way to create writing by taking text that already exists and subtracting words/phrases to make something new from what is already written.

To learn more, check out the following video about how to do blackout poetry, created by Austin Kleon, an artist who has published an entire book of newspaper blackout poems! https\://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wKpVgoGr6kE&feature=emb_title

Here are some submissions from Mrs. Delsordo's, Mrs. Hirt's, Mrs. Murphy's, Mrs. Salgado's, Mrs. Shea's, Mrs. Kutufaris's and Miss Wilkins's classes!

Shrek at SHMS
March 6, 2015

It is really a treat to see so many excellent shows at SHHS and SHMS and watch our talented students perform. The set design, costumes, makeup, lights, ushers, music, and more is always first class. The students, directors, choreographers, and all of the staff work so hard to bring us these amazing shows. I am in awe of the students' talent.

I am glad we were able to see Chicago this year too, before everything changed. I saw my first performance of Les Mis at SHHS and it was truly life-changing. I am always hounding Mr. Shankweiler for the cast list as I am excited to see who got which parts - and I also go check the posted list at SHMS too. Bravo to our theater department!

post_text: Thanks to South Media Fire Companyand Garden City Fire Company #1 for keeping our community safe and providing an opportunity for our students, graduates, teachers, and community members to serve and make a difference.
shared_text:
South Media Fire Company
May 5 at 1:28 PM ¬∑

As many of us stay at home and turn our attention to our yards, we are smart to consider that mulch can (if conditions right with heat and depth) self ignite. The most common cause of a mulch fire is a carelessly discarded cigarette. Don't smoke? Mulch clearly doesn't care, as it can set itself on fire anyway ;)

While we don't know the cause of the mulch fire at Strath Haven MS this morning, we do know that it took a Strath Haven High School graduate and a current Haven student, with shovels and pressurized water and before upgrading to a handline, to fully extinguish this fire at the Copples Lane entrance to the Middle School.

Before you dump that mulch, google a 'How To'.
South Media Fire Company
Garden City Fire Company #1

Sixth grade language arts students in Mrs. Hirt's, Mrs. Shea's, and Miss Wilkins's language arts classes spent the month of April studying poetry, considering craft moves made by authors, and creating their own poems utilizing some of those moves. Two mentor texts that inspired student writing were "On Turning Ten" by Billy Collins and "Gratitude" by Jennifer Dignan.

Mrs. Hirt, Mrs. Shea, and Miss Wilkins are proud of all of their students for utilizing their voices and exploring poetry to connect with themselves and their communities during this experience. The classes also extend an invitation for anyone inspired by this poetry to craft their own poems inspired by "On Turning Ten" and/or "Gratitude." Happy writing! Thank you, students, for sharing your poetry with us!

‚ÄúGrit is passion and perseverance for very long-term goals. Grit is having stamina. Grit is sticking with your future, day-in, day-out. Not just for the week, not just for the month, but for years. And working really hard to make that future a reality. Grit is living life like it‚Äôs a marathon, not a sprint.‚Äù - Dr. Angela Lee Duckworth

post_text:
Students in Ms. Corson's 5th grade class at SRS brought a proposal to Swarthmore Borough and Rutledge Borough, Rutledge, PA to recognize Indigenous People's Day. Swarthmore passed a resolution on March 9th, and Rutledge passed one on April 20th. Although Rutledge Borough Council was disappointed to pass it remotely, they were happy the students were able to watch on Facebook live. They look forward to celebrating this fall!

The resolution reads:

Rutledge Borough Council proclaims the Friday in September closest to the Harvest Moon henceforth be commemorated as Indigenous Peoples‚Äô Day. Council encourages residents of the Borough, businesses, organizations, our schools and all public institutions to reflect upon the ongoing struggles of Indigenous peoples of this land, to stand in solidarity with Indigenous peoples everywhere and to celebrate the thriving cultures and values of the Indigenous Peoples of this region in whatever ways they see fit to commemorate this day.

Well done!

Happy Teacher Appreciation Week!

We are grateful to our WSSD teachers who do so much for our students, families, community, and each other year in and year out. We are particularly thankful for the incredible pivot they made to embark on this new journey to finish out the school year. We know how hard they are working and how much they want to be back in school with their students. Let's take the time to thank them!

Ideas to thank your teachers, aides, and other staff that help you inside and outside of your classrooms:

üåà REFLECT: Share a favorite memory or story of a teacher that has had an impact on you - from this year or in the past.

üñç CREATE: Make a sign, draw a picture, write a poem, make sidewalk chalk art, or create a video message thanking your teacher(s).

üëè THANK: Give a shout out to a specific teacher or teachers that you wish to acknowledge during this week.

Send an email to them, make a post using #wssdteachers, or message this page. Alumni, we would love to hear from you too!

post_text:
If you tuned in to watch the NFL draft on Friday night, you may have seen WES fith grade student Dominique Bottino and her family among the Philadelphia Eagles virtual fans!

As an ambassador for the Eagles Autism Foundation, Dominique was chosen to be a part of the NFL Inner Circle and virtually cheer on the Eagles as they announced their picks. She and her family had rehearsals with the NFL, watched from behind the scenes through the live stream, sat in on virtual meet and greets with the picks, and cheered on national TV as they announced their 2nd round pick, Jalen Hurts and 3rd round pick, Davion Taylor.

Her mom Nicole said, "Dominique was so excited to be their cheerleader and shake her pom poms as they made the announcements! Truly an amazing night we will never forget!"

Awesome! What a very memorable experience for Dominique and her family! Thank you, Eagles! #flyeaglesfly ü¶Ö

However, this stay-at-home experience has proven to me that our elders‚Äô worry is unnecessary. Because isolation isn‚Äôt in human nature, and no advancement in technology could replace our need to meet in person, especially when it comes to learning."

A high five to Strath Haven High School students Eric Tao, Thomas Hsu, and Ben Kedson who are eligible to compete in the virtual American Computer Science League All-Star contest!

The competition consists of 4 tests taken during the school year. Although the Haven students were on a team, eligibility for this year's contest was determined by the cumulative individual scores on each of these tests.

These team members will participate in late May in a contest where they will be given three hours to write a program meeting certain specifications, and one hour to answer a series of short-response questions.

Congratulations, Eric, Thomas, and Ben, and good luck! #wssdhighfive #havenproud

https://www.acsl.org/
https://marc6888.wixsite.com/acsl/all-star-contest-information

A high five to Strath Haven High School students Cassie Savukinas, Nate Bartlett, and Francis Fletcher who have been virtually teaching free robotics classes to kids in grades K through 8 since the middle of March! They teach programming and engineering as well as conduct virtual teamwork challenges.

They are part of a FIRST Robotics program and were previously running classes in person. They then created these virtual classes and opened them up to kids from anywhere. They designed the curriculum on their own, adapting to new kids coming in each week and no one having actual robots to program.

For more info about the class email epraprograms@gmail.com or check out Eastern Pennsylvania Robotics Alliance.

#nationalhighfiveday #havenproud

post_text:
NPE first grade student Mia Warren has been busy during this break sharing her artwork and words of encouragement to brighten up other people's days.

After making and displaying a banner thanking all healthcare professionals for taking care of us during this COVID-19 outbreak, the Director of Patient Experience at Penn Presbyterian Medical Center saw the sign and asked Mia to make cards for hospital patients. Mia not only responded, but she answered with a big heart! Mia‚Äôs efforts were fully supported by Mrs. Getty, her first grade teacher at NPE, with words of encouragement and praise every step of the way (virtually, of course)!

Mia has been making felt heart necklaces, rainbow pictures and cards. and butterflies. Mia used a rainbow template that Mrs. Adams (third grade teacher at NPE) gave to her older brother, Andrew. Friends also donated crossword puzzle books and sudoku books, that were given along with homemade word find books that Mia made for patients to do when they felt better in the hospital.

Great job, Mia!

The WSSD Student Meal Program began on Thursday, April 2nd with 340 children served for a total of 2,720 meals!

The program, for children 18 and under, continues this week with a new schedule and location. Meals will be available on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays at Strath Haven High School from 10 a.m. - 12 p.m.

THIS WEEK ONLY, the pick-up days will be Monday, Wednesday, and Thursday due to spring break being on Friday.

- Please use the Brookhaven Road entrance.

- Be sure to preregister for the program so the Food Service Department can prepare accordingly, This only needs to be done once, so If you have previously registered you do not need to do so again. https://forms.gle/7kC43UuKgx7M6qss8

- Learn more about the program here: wssd.org/foodandnutrition

Students in Mrs. McLead's Girls Go CyberStart Club at Strath Haven High School met on Zoom yesterday and had a special guest visitor - Karlie Kloss! In addition to being a supermodel and Project Runway host, Karlie runs an organization called Kode With Klossy where she encourages girls to learn to code and design apps through programs and summer camps.

Karlie got connected with the club through Alana Mackey who has attended the camp the past two years. Karlie wanted to drop in on a class for an April Fool's Day visit and share some encouragement for girls in IT! What a fun surprise!

https://girlsgocyberstart.org/

Congratulations to SHHS junior Luke Edwards for being named first team All-Central! He was the team's MVP with 15 ppg and ranking high in Delco for 3 pointers. He led on and off the court and helped the team make their historic run all the way to the state playoffs. He scored 414 points this season and needs 296 to make it to the 1,000 point club his senior year. Great job, Luke! #havenproud

A little reminiscing by the Delco Times sports reporter, Matt Smith:

"...In the meantime, we must kill more time from our social distancing caves. Let‚Äôs take a deep dive into some of the best Delco hoops stories of the 2019-20 campaign."

"STRATH HAVEN'S EPIC TURNAROUND
The Panthers posted a 17-11 record and earned a state tournament berth for the first time in nine years. Not bad for a program in shambles just one year ago when it managed a grand total of three wins.

A lot of credit can be heaped on rookie head coach Chris Conlan and his staff. Conlan took the gig at Strath Haven following a handful of seasons learning from one of the best in the county, Mike Doyle at Penncrest. In the first round of states, the Panthers for one half gave Archbishop Wood a real scare. Nevertheless, it was a memorable season for the Panthers, who should be among the top dogs in the Central League next winter." üêæüèÄ

post_text:
Good luck to Strath Haven alumna Allie Wilson as she works to qualify for the now 2021 Olympic Games. We are proud of you!

"Thunderstorms delayed Allie Wilson‚Äôs training schedule Tuesday morning. By that time she had heard the news that the International Olympic Committee had postponed the 2020 Summer Games in Tokyo to 2021 in the wake of the coronavirus pandemic.

A few hours later, organizers from TrackTown USA announced that the U.S. Olympic Track & Field Trials, slated for June 19-28 at the University of Oregon have also been rescheduled to next year.

As a first-year pro looking to qualify for the Trials for the first time in her career, the five-time two-sport All-Delco from Strath Haven and three-time All-American from Monmouth University Track & Field was disappointed, but understanding."

post_text:
#WSSDSPIRITWEEK

Day 1, Monday, 3/23 - Superhero Day!

Our teachers and staff are missing their students A LOT. They are a pretty extraordinary and dedicated group, and we all can't wait to get back into school and our classrooms. During Halloween, and throughout the school year, they really show their spirit and sense of fun.

Dress as your favorite superhero today. It could be Wonder Woman or Batman. It could be your favorite teacher. It could be your parent who is a doctor or nurse who is at work today and who may be quarantined from your family during this time. It could be a figure from history or a character from a book or a sports icon. Whoever you want. Embrace their spirit for the day and use their strength, and our communal strength to get through this. Together we can!

post_text:
A message for rising 9th through 12th grade students from Mrs. LaPira, interim principal:

The high school course registration portal will close Friday, March 20th at 7:00 p.m. By tomorrow evening, it is important for your child to have their course selection complete and submitted, including core courses, elective, fifth block music, and alternate elective choices.

The directions to complete course registration are on the front page of the high school webpage. Students will use wssd.powerschool.com/public and use their student ID number as a username and password. Students who don't know their password may reach out to request it.

It is very important that our course selection process continues during this absence from school, as it is just the first step of many in the process to ensure that students are properly scheduled for next school year. Mrs. Lawson and I are happy to answer questions as they arise.

shared_text:
SHHS Art Department
March 14 at 3:58 PM ¬∑

With the closure of all WSSD schools and the closure of the Community Art Center through March 30, we are sad to report that our biennial K-12 art exhibition The Art of WSSD is closed until further notice. The reception scheduled for March 22 is canceled.

The Art of WSSD was installed over the course of two days earlier this week by students in AP Art & Design. We typically have four days to install this show but only had two days to complete this daunting task due to circumstances beyond our control. Seniors in AP Art & Design worked incredibly hard to prepare, organize, and hang over 100 works of art created by students from every grade in the school district. Many thanks to the AP Art & Design class for making this exhibition possible. Their efforts make the art from our K-12 students shine brightly on the walls of the Duke Gallery at CAC. We are proud of all of our artists from every grade from each school in the district who had art selected for this exhibition. #theartofwssd

post_text:
PIAA Class 3A Swimming and Diving Championships Recap

In the 200 yard freestyle preliminaries on Wednesday, Sydney Bergstrom placed 13th with a time of 1:52.93 and Mia Yancey was 26th in 1:55.92.

Sydney advanced to the B finals that evening where she placed second in a time of 1:50.95 - which would have placed her 4th in the A final. Despite her fast time, she finished 10th overall.

On Thursday, Sydney finished third in the 500 yard freestyle preliminaries in a time of 4:56.75. She did not get a chance to swim the finals that evening as the competition was canceled before then - so her third place finish stood.

Congratulations to both swimmers on a great season! Mia is a junior and Sydney is a sophomore, and they are both looking forward to next year and getting back to the state championships again. #havenproud

Results: http://www.piaa.org/news/details.aspx?ID=3254

State Champion! Congratulations to Hannah Spielman who won her division at the MyHouse PA High School Girls Folkstyle Wrestling Championships last weekend!

"It was all Delaware County at 147, where Strath Haven‚Äôs Hannah Spielman toed the line across from Chichester‚Äôs Dymanique Jones. Spielman was in complete control all match, picking up a pair of takedowns and three near fall on the way to an 8-2 decision."

Hannah's final match: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lsoiu-KBiro

Post-tournament interview: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PjaRPy4rH2A

Read more about the competition and the growth of girls wresetling: https://papreplive.com/2020/03/10/girls-wrestling-championships-demonstrate-need-for-piaa-sanctioning/

Congratulations, Hannah! #hardwork #HavenProud

post_text: The WSSD Music Department was very excited to host David Kim, world-renowned violinist and concertmaster of the Philadelphia Orchestra on March 2nd! He gave a clinic and masterclass to all of our WSSD string students from 4th through 12th grade. The SHHS orchestra performed, and Mr. Kim gave feedback to the whole group as well as to individual musicians. He shared stories of his early years learning the violin, studying at Juilliard, performing with Yo-Yo Ma and about his violin which was made c. 1757. It was a wonderful experience for our students and music teachers! Thank you, Mr. Kim, for visiting us! üéª

On to Hershey!

Congratulations to SHHS wrestlers Gabe Federico and Chase Barlow who are headed to the PIAA state championships in Hershey!

Gabe, a junior, battled his way through the 182 lb bracket at the South East AAA Regional Championships to place 5th and earn his first trip to states!

Chase, a sophomore, qualified for states for the second year in a row with a fourth place finish at 132 lbs.

Great job to all of the Haven wrestlers who competed this weekend and to the coaches on a great meet. Good luck at states!

From a record of 3-19 in 2018-2019 to a 17-9 record and a trip to the state playoffs a year later (first time since 2009!), read how first year head coach Chris Conlan and the Strath Haven Men's Basketball team have set a new standard of excellence for the program.

The team defeated Holy Ghost Prep 54-46 on Wednesday night to keep their season alive. They will play at Unionville on Friday night in the fifth place game of the District 1 tournament, and then will get ready for the state playoffs beginning on Friday, March 6th. Way to go, Strath Haven! üêæüèÄ
